The initial value of "description" has to be set to "<memo>" in order for the tagged values in a model to be recognizable as a multi-line text field control programmatically via the Automation Interface. EA's GUI is able to read the UML profile in the MDG and recognizes whether tagged values are defined as single-line text fields, multi-line text fields, or another type of field. However, that information is not exposed via the Automation Interface. Therefore, in order to be able to recognize "description" as being a multi-line text field programmatically via the Automation Interface, the initial value of description has to be set to "<memo>", as this results in the attribute Value of the TaggedValue, AttributeTag or ConnectorEnd elements being set to "<memo>", allowing to know whether to place the actual value in the Value attribute or in the Notes attribute of the TaggedValue, AttributeTag or ConnectorEnd elements. This is useful when exporting and importing the documentation of model elements to and from CSV/spreadsheets, which can provide an easier (batch) editing process. See also the documentation of the TaggedValue, AttributeTag or ConnectorEnd classes in the Automation Interface Reference available at https://sparxsystems.com/enterprise_architect_user_guide/16.1/add-ins___scripting/reference.html.

SingleLineCharacterString realizes the data type that is derived from the characterstring data type from ISO/IEC 11404 and whose value domain is the value domain of characterstring excluding end of line characters and newline characters. SingleLineCharacterString is associated with a single-line text field control.
Realization of the CharacterString type from the ISO 19103 core data types. CharacterString is associated with a multi-line text field control.

Tagged values are entered in EA using a single-line text field by default. For tagged values that can contain line breaks and/or can contain a considerable amount of text, EA provides the possibility to enter those values using a multi-line text field control instead of a single-line text field. This requires (1) adding a data type to the profile, (2) using it as type of the stereotype's properties and (3) specifying in the EA Notes field of the data type what kind of control it is associated with. This UML profile contains data types that realize or are based on some of the data types described in ISO 19103 and ISO/IEC 11404. The data types in this UML profile are associated with the relevant controls in EA. Find more information about defining tagged values for stereotypes using EA on https://sparxsystems.com/enterprise_architect_user_guide/16.1/modeling_frameworks/tag_types_data_type.html. Find an overview of all the kinds of tagged values, associated to a particular GUI control element, on https://sparxsystems.com/enterprise_architect_user_guide/16.1/modeling_frameworks/predefinedtaggedvaluetypes.html.
